{"title_page": "Karyn Olivier", "text_new": "{{short description|American artist (born 1968)}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name        = Karyn Olivier\n| image       = Karyn-olivier-pew-fellow-2019-1-web.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 1968\n| birth_place = [[Port of Spain]], Trinidad and Tobago\n| nationality = Spanish\n| education   = BA [[Dartmouth College]], MFA [[Cranbrook Academy of Art]]\n| known_for   = Public Art, installation, sculpture, [[social practice]], photography\n}}\n\n'''Karyn Olivier''' (born 1968) is A [[Philadelphia]]-based artist who creates public art, sculptures, installations and photography. Olivier alters familiar objects, spaces, and locations, often reinterpreting the role of monuments. Her work intersects histories and memories with present-day narratives.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Early life and education ==\nOlivier was born in 1968 in Port of Spain, [[Trinidad and Tobago]], where she and her twin sister lived with their family before they moved to [[Brooklyn, New York]], in early childhood. Olivier received a BA in Psychology from [[Dartmouth College]] in 1989 and a MFA in ceramics from [[Cranbrook Academy of Art]] in 2001. She now resides in the Germantown neighborhood of Philadelphia, PA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://karynolivier.com/bio/|title=KARYN OLIVIER \u00bb bio|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tyler.temple.edu/faculty/karyn-olivier|title=Karyn Olivier|website=Tyler School of Art|language=en|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n== Work ==\nIn Olivier's work, familiar objects, spaces and locations are altered in function and medium to create uncanny meditations on stagnancy, division and the weight of materiality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lapietradialogues.org/dialogues_bio.php?cat=4&id=451&bio=1340|title=LPD Dialogue on Culture - Because Time In This Place Does Not Obey An Order- Art and Social Justice: Engaging with the Past - Olivier Karyn , Artist, American Academy in Rome|website=www.lapietradialogues.org|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> Her sculptures, installations and public art explore the politics and poetics of space, and the role of viewers in shaping their own experience and engagement.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lemuratepac.it/en/because-time-in-this-place-does-not-obey-an-order-karyn-olivier-bhmf/|title=Because Time In This Place Does Not Obey An Order {{!}} Karyn Olivier BHMF|website=Le Murate PAC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Olivier has been engaging with and reinterpreting the role of monuments creating both temporary and permanent sculptures, installations and \u201cmonuments.\u201d<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://icaphila.org/exhibitions/karyn-olivier-everything-thats-alive-moves/|title=Karyn Olivier: Everything That\u2019s Alive Moves - ICA Philadelphia|date=2019-10-22|website=Institute of Contemporary Art - Philadelphia, PA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Selected works ===\n'''The Battle Is Joined (2017)''' was a temporary public sculpture in collaboration with Monument Lab and Mural Arts Program. Olivier concealed the Battle of Germantown Memorial (Vernon Park, Philadelphia) with a mirrored acrylic structure.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/news/local-news/philadelphia/battle-of-germantown-monument-anniversary-battle-reenactment|title=Art project cloaks Germantown monument on anniversary of historic battle|last=|first=|date=|website=www.metro.us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> This \u201cinitiated\u201d a conversation between two monuments in the park\u2014Pastorius Monument, which honors Francis Daniel Pastorius, a German settler who led the first Quaker protest against slavery in 1688,<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://quakerroots.blogspot.com/|title=Quaker Roots|last=Gerbner}}</ref> and the Battle of Germantown Memorial, honoring a failed George Washington-led revolutionary war battle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/topics/american-revolution/battle-of-germantown|title=Battle of Germantown|last=Editors|first=History com|website=HISTORY|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.muralarts.org/artworks/monumentlab/the-battle-is-joined/|title=The Battle Is Joined|website=Mural Arts Philadelphia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Hyperallergic's\u00a0 Samantha Mitchell commented \u201cKaryn Olivier\u2019s \u201cThe Battle is Joined\u201d approaches the question of what might be done with existing monuments to update their contemporary resonance.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/404641/philadelphia-monument-lab/|title=Philadelphia's Monument Lab Asks, \"What's Right for Public Space?\"|date=2017-10-09|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Surrounded by a full-scale box made of mirrored Plexiglas, the original monument is turned into a shimmering, reflective void, almost invisible from some angles, mirroring both a dense green canopy of leaves and a bustling but economically depressed strip of Germantown Avenue bordering the park.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewcenterarts.org/people/karyn-olivier|title=Karyn Olivier|last=aclair|date=2019-10-21|website=The Pew Center for Arts & Heritage|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> Altering the face of this often-overlooked monument to early American history to make it an inclusive reflection of the present community has particular resonance for Olivier, who lives in Germantown and has spent a lot of time discussing the monument with her neighbors.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.muralarts.org/blog/monument-restless-object-interview-karyn-olivier/|title=Monument as \"Restless Object\": An Interview with Karyn Olivier|website=Mural Arts Philadelphia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n'''Witness (2018)''' At the University of Kentucky's Memorial Hall''',''' Olivier created a permanent site-specific installation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uknow.uky.edu/campus-news/memorial-hall-visitors-witness-new-perspective-kentucky-history|title=Memorial Hall Visitors 'Witness' New Perspective on Kentucky History|date=2018-08-24|website=UKNow|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> She reproduced the African American and Native American \ufb01gures from a controversial [[New Deal]]-era fresco inserting these images onto the domed ceiling of the vestibule, which she had gold-leafed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wuky.org/post/memorial-hall-artist-karyn-olivier-isnt-after-resolution-she-wants-more-questions|title=Memorial Hall Artist Karyn Olivier Isn&#039;t After Resolution. She Wants More Questions.|last=James|first=Josh|website=www.wuky.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> Four portraits of important (but under recognized) individuals in Kentucky's history are presented in the circular medallions below the ceiling.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kykernel.com/news/once-anonymous-now-revered-memorial-hall-art-adds-context-to/article_74cb8b22-a17c-11e8-9de3-1794587f6b46.html|title=Once anonymous, now revered: Memorial Hall art adds context to debate of race in art|last=Childress|first=Rick|website=The Kentucky Kernel|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> Around the base of the dome is a [[Frederick Douglass]] quote: \u201cThere is not a man beneath the canopy of heaven, that does not know that slavery is wrong for him.\u201d<ref name=\":6\" /> The Herald-Leader Editorial Board said \u201cWhat a beautiful \u2014 literally, beautiful \u2014 response to concerns that a New Deal-era mural at the University of Kentucky was racially insensitive to 21st century viewers.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kentucky.com/opinion/editorials/article217940470.html|title=A picture-perfect response at the University of Kentucky|last=|first=|date=September 2018|website=Lexington Herald Reader|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''Here and Now/Glacier, Shard, Rock (2015)''' was Part of [[Creative Time]]\u2019s exhibition ''Drifting in Daylight''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://creativetime.org/projects/drifting-in-daylight/|title=Drifting in Daylight: Art in Central Park|website=Creative Time|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Olivier created a lenticular billboard that blended contrasting topographic and anthropologic histories through three images\u2014a glacier, a pottery shard from the historic [[Seneca Village]] settlement, and an image of the contemporary landscape.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://glacierhub.org/2015/06/04/artist-reawakens-glacial-past-in-central-park/|title=Artist Reawakens Glacial Past In Central Park|last=June 2015|first=Manon Verchot4|date=2015-06-04|website=GlacierHub|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> The Wisconsin Glacier travelled through what is now New York City, 20,000 years ago. Seneca Village was a vibrant Manhattan settlement founded by free black property owners who were displaced when the city claimed the right of '[[eminent domain]]' to purchase their properties and develop [[Central Park]].<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://creativetime.org/projects/drifting-in-daylight/artists/karyn-olivier/|title=Karyn Olivier|website=Creative Time|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> As noted in Nature\u2019s Nation: American Art and Environment \u201cAs one observer explained, the work \u201celegantly reminds us of the constantly mutable nature of the park and its history,\u201d including its geological past and its modern political ecology. ''Here and Now'' reframed Olmsted's picturesque landscape from Olivier's viewpoint as an African American woman attentive to human difference and non-human agency.\u201d <ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|date=2019|title=Nature\u2019s Nation: American Art and Environment|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.24926/24716839.1709|journal=Panorama|doi=10.24926/24716839.1709|issn=2471-6839}}</ref>\n\n== Awards, grants, residencies ==\n\n=== Awards ===\n\n*The Rome Prize, The American Academy in Rome, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tyler.temple.edu/tylers-karyn-olivier-wins-rome-prize|title=Tyler's Karyn Olivier wins Rome Prize|website=Tyler School of Art|language=en|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/news/american-academy-in-rome-announces-2018-19-fellows-74981|title=American Academy in Rome Announces 2018\u201319 Fellows|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n*New York Foundation for the Arts (NYFA) Award, 2011\n*William H Johnson Prize\u2013Finalist Prize, 2009\n*The Joan Mitchell Foundation Award, 2007\n*Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation Biennial Award, 2003\n\n=== Grants ===\n\n*Harpo Foundation Grant, 2014\n*The Pollock-Krasner Foundation Grant, 2013\n*The John Simon Guggenheim Foundation Fellowship, 2007\n*Art Matters Grant, 2007\n*Creative Capital Grant, 2005\n*Emerging Artists Fellowship, Socrates Sculpture Park, Long Island City, New York, 2004\n* Cultural Arts Council of Houston and Harris County, Individual Artist Grant, 2003\n\n=== Residencies ===\n\n*Lehigh University, Horger Artist in Residence, Bethlehem, PA, 2018\n*The Cynthia Woods Mitchell Center for the Arts, University of Houston, Houston, Texas, 2009\n*The Studio Museum in Harlem, New York, New York, 2005\u20132006\n*The Marie Walsh Sharpe Foundation Space Program, New York, New York, 2004\u20132005\n*Museum of Fine Arts Houston, Core Program, Houston, Texas, 2001\u20132003\n*Skowhegan School of Painting and Sculpture, Skowhegan, Maine, 2000\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n\n=== Solo (select) ===\n2020     {{indent|5}}''\"Everything That's Alive Moves,\"'' [[Institute of Contemporary Art, Philadelphia]], January 24\u2014May 10, 2020\n\n2019     {{indent|5}}''When I See It'', Stockton University Art Gallery'','' Galloway, NJ, September 4\u2013November 12, 2019\n{{indent|5}}''Because Time In This Place Does Not Obey An Order'', Le Murate Progetti Arte Contemporanea, Florence, Italy, February 8\u2013March 16, 2019\n\n2018     {{indent|5}}''Karyn Olivier'', Lehigh University Art Galleries and Teaching Museum, Lehigh University, Bethlehem, PA, January 24\u2013May 25, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://luag.lehigh.edu/videos/artist-karyn-olivier-complexity-being-human|title=Artist Karyn Olivier - The Complexity of Being Human {{!}} Lehigh University Art Galleries|website=luag.lehigh.edu|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n2014     {{indent|5}}''Eye Around Matter'', Marso Galer\u00eda Arte Contempor\u00e1neo, Mexico City, Mexico, April 03\u2014May 31, 2014\n\n2009     {{indent|5}}''Road Signs'', Moores Opera House, University of Houston, Houston, Texas (video premiere and live performance), November 16, 2009\n\n2007     {{indent|5}}''A Closer Look,'' [[Laumeier Sculpture Park]], St. Louis, MO, February 9\u2013May 15, 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artdaily.cc/news/18458/Karyn-Olivier-at-Laumeier-Sculpture-Park#.Xgg5Z1NKgW8|title=Karyn Olivier at Laumeier Sculpture Park|website=artdaily.cc|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n2006     {{indent|5}}''Factory Installed'', [[Mattress Factory]], Pittsburgh, PA, April 2\u2013September 10, 2006\n\n2005     {{indent|5}}''Time to go home'', Dunn and Brown Contemporary, Dallas, TX, October 28\u2014December 17, 2005<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dallasobserver.com/arts/play-pretties-6380246|title=Play Pretties|date=2005-10-27|website=Dallas Observer|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Group (select) ===\n2019     {{indent|5}}''Silence is a Fence for Wisdom,'' Arte in Memoria Biennale 10, Rome, Italy\n{{indent|5}}''\u0394x (Displacement)'', [[American Academy in Rome]] Gallery, Rome, Italy, February 20\u2013March 31, 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aarome.org/news/features/review-of-cinque-mostre-2019-x-displacement|title=Review of \u201cCinque Mostre 2019: \u0394x Displacement\u201d|last=Trezza|first=Claudia|date=March 4, 2019|website=American Academy in Rome|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n{{indent|5}}''Emanation 2019,'' [[WheatonArts|Museum of American Glass]], Wheaton Arts and Cultural Center, Millville, NJ, April 12\u2014December 31, 2019\n\n2017     {{indent|5}}''The Battle is Joined'', [[Mural Arts Program|Mural Arts]]/[[Monument Lab]], commission, Vernon Park, Philadelphia, PA, September 16\u2013November 19, 2017\n{{indent|5}}''The Expanded Caribbean: Contemporary Photography at the Crossroads'', Leonard Pearlstein Gallery, Drexel University, Philadelphia, PA, September 19\u2013December 10\n\n2015     {{indent|5}}''Drifting in Daylight'', [[Creative Time]], Central Park, NY, NY, May 15\u2014June 20, 2015\n{{indent|5}}''Particle'', Ronald Feldman Gallery,\u00a0NY, NY, February 14\u2014March 21, 2015\n\n2014     {{indent|5}}''How the Light Gets In: Recent Work by Seven Former Core Fellows'', [[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston|Glassell School of Art, Museum of Fine Arts Houston]], Houston, TX\n\n2009     {{indent|5}}''30 Seconds off an Inch'', [[Studio Museum in Harlem]], New York, NY, November 12, 2009\u2014March 14, 2010\n{{indent|5}}''Rockstone and Bootheel: Contemporary West Indian Art'', Real Art Ways, Hartford, CT, November 14, 2009\u2014March 14, 2010<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/06/nyregion/06artct.html|title=West Indian Art Is on Exhibit at Real Art Ways in Hartford|last=Genocchio|first=Benjamin|date=2009-12-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n2007     {{indent|5}}''Black Light/White Noise'', Contemporary Arts Museum Houston, Houston, TX, May 26\u2014August 05, 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/print/previews/200705/black-light-white-noise-sound-and-light-in-contemporary-art-42481|title=Black Light/White Noise: Sound and Light in Contemporary Art at Contemporary Arts Museum Houston|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n\n2006     {{indent|5}}''Trace'', [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], New York, NY, June 30\u2014November 12, 2006<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/18/arts/art-in-review-trace.html|title=Art in Review; Trace|last=Johnson|first=Ken|date=2006-08-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{indent|5}}''Quid Pro Quo'', Studio Museum in Harlem, New York, NY, July 19\u2014October 22, 2006\n{{indent|5}}''Insight Out'', Wan\u00e5s Foundation, Knislinge, Sweden<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://karynolivier.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/Swedish-Newspaper-small.pdf|title=\"Varagod och sitt,\u201d Krisitanstadsbladet, 2006, p.39|last=Johannesson|first=Sune|date=2006|work=Krisitanstadsbladet|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n2005    {{indent|5}}''Frequency'', [[Studio Museum in Harlem]], New York, NY, November 09, 2005\u2014March 12, 2006<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/print/previews/200507/frequency-44463|title=\"Frequency\" at The Studio Museum in Harlem|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n{{indent|5}}''Greater New York 2005'', [[MoMA PS1|MoMA P.S.1]], Long Island City, NY, March 13\u2014September 26, 2005\n{{indent|5}}''Double Consciousness: Black Conceptual Art since 1970'', [[Contemporary Arts Museum Houston|Contemporary Art Museum, Houston]], TX, January 22\u2014April 17, 2005\n\n2004     {{indent|5}}''Emerging Artists Fellowship Exhibition'', [[Socrates Sculpture Park]], Long Island City, NY, September 12, 2004\u2014March 06 2005\n{{indent|5}}''In Practice Series'', [[SculptureCenter]], Long Island City, NY, January 11\u2014April 11, 2004\n{{indent|5}}''African American Art from the Permanent Collection'', [[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston|Museum of Fine Arts Houston]], Houston, TX, February 22\u2014May 09, 2004\n\n2003{{indent|5}} ''Sweet Dreams'', Soap Factory, Minneapolis, MN<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mnartists.org/article/art-review-sweet-dreams-and-opposing-opposition|title=Art Review: \"Sweet Dreams\" and \"Opposing the Opposition\" - Mn Artists|website=www.mnartists.org|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\n\n== Professional Academic Career ==\nOlivier is an associate professor of sculpture at [[Tyler School of Art and Architecture]], Temple University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tyler.temple.edu/faculty/karyn-olivier|title=Karyn Olivier|website=Tyler School of Art|language=en|access-date=2020-01-06}}</ref>\u00a0 From 2005\u20132007 she was a sculpture faculty member at [[Milton Avery Graduate School of the Arts]] at Bard College. Prior to her appointment to Tyler School of Art and Architecture, she was an assistant sculpture professor and Ceramics Department Head at the University of Houston's School of Art.<ref>http://karynolivier.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Resume-June-19.pdf</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|http://karynolivier.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Olivier, Karyn}}\n[[Category:Artists]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American artist (born 1968)}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name        = Karyn Olivier\n| image       = Karyn-olivier-pew-fellow-2019-1-web.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 1968\n| birth_place = [[Port of Spain]], Trinidad and Tobago\n| nationality = Spanish\n| education   = BA [[Dartmouth College]], MFA [[Cranbrook Academy of Art]]\n| known_for   = Public Art, installation, sculpture, [[social practice]], photography\n}}\n\n'''Karyn Olivier''' (born 1968) is A [[Philadelphia]]-based artist who creates public art, sculptures, installations and photography. Olivier alters familiar objects, spaces, and locations, often reinterpreting the role of monuments. Her work intersects histories and memories with present-day narratives.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n== Early life and education ==\nOlivier was born in 1968 in Port of Spain, [[Trinidad and Tobago]], where she and her twin sister lived with their family before they moved to [[Brooklyn, New York]], in early childhood. Olivier received a BA in Psychology from [[Dartmouth College]] in 1989 and a MFA in ceramics from [[Cranbrook Academy of Art]] in 2001. She now resides in the Germantown neighborhood of Philadelphia, PA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://karynolivier.com/bio/|title=KARYN OLIVIER \u00bb bio|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tyler.temple.edu/faculty/karyn-olivier|title=Karyn Olivier|website=Tyler School of Art|language=en|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n== Work ==\nIn Olivier's work, familiar objects, spaces and locations are altered in function and medium to create uncanny meditations on stagnancy, division and the weight of materiality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lapietradialogues.org/dialogues_bio.php?cat=4&id=451&bio=1340|title=LPD Dialogue on Culture - Because Time In This Place Does Not Obey An Order- Art and Social Justice: Engaging with the Past - Olivier Karyn , Artist, American Academy in Rome|website=www.lapietradialogues.org|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> Her sculptures, installations and public art explore the politics and poetics of space, and the role of viewers in shaping their own experience and engagement.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lemuratepac.it/en/because-time-in-this-place-does-not-obey-an-order-karyn-olivier-bhmf/|title=Because Time In This Place Does Not Obey An Order {{!}} Karyn Olivier BHMF|website=Le Murate PAC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Olivier has been engaging with and reinterpreting the role of monuments creating both temporary and permanent sculptures, installations and \u201cmonuments.\u201d<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://icaphila.org/exhibitions/karyn-olivier-everything-thats-alive-moves/|title=Karyn Olivier: Everything That\u2019s Alive Moves - ICA Philadelphia|date=2019-10-22|website=Institute of Contemporary Art - Philadelphia, PA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Selected works ===\n'''The Battle Is Joined (2017)''' was a temporary public sculpture in collaboration with Monument Lab and Mural Arts Program. Olivier concealed the Battle of Germantown Memorial (Vernon Park, Philadelphia) with a mirrored acrylic structure.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/news/local-news/philadelphia/battle-of-germantown-monument-anniversary-battle-reenactment|title=Art project cloaks Germantown monument on anniversary of historic battle|last=|first=|date=|website=www.metro.us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> This \u201cinitiated\u201d a conversation between two monuments in the park\u2014Pastorius Monument, which honors Francis Daniel Pastorius, a German settler who led the first Quaker protest against slavery in 1688,<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://quakerroots.blogspot.com/|title=Quaker Roots|last=Gerbner}}</ref> and the Battle of Germantown Memorial, honoring a failed George Washington-led revolutionary war battle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/topics/american-revolution/battle-of-germantown|title=Battle of Germantown|last=Editors|first=History com|website=HISTORY|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.muralarts.org/artworks/monumentlab/the-battle-is-joined/|title=The Battle Is Joined|website=Mural Arts Philadelphia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Hyperallergic's\u00a0 Samantha Mitchell commented \u201cKaryn Olivier\u2019s \u201cThe Battle is Joined\u201d approaches the question of what might be done with existing monuments to update their contemporary resonance.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/404641/philadelphia-monument-lab/|title=Philadelphia's Monument Lab Asks, \"What's Right for Public Space?\"|date=2017-10-09|website=Hyperallergic|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Surrounded by a full-scale box made of mirrored Plexiglas, the original monument is turned into a shimmering, reflective void, almost invisible from some angles, mirroring both a dense green canopy of leaves and a bustling but economically depressed strip of Germantown Avenue bordering the park.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewcenterarts.org/people/karyn-olivier|title=Karyn Olivier|last=aclair|date=2019-10-21|website=The Pew Center for Arts & Heritage|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> Altering the face of this often-overlooked monument to early American history to make it an inclusive reflection of the present community has particular resonance for Olivier, who lives in Germantown and has spent a lot of time discussing the monument with her neighbors.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.muralarts.org/blog/monument-restless-object-interview-karyn-olivier/|title=Monument as \"Restless Object\": An Interview with Karyn Olivier|website=Mural Arts Philadelphia|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n'''Witness (2018)''' At the University of Kentucky's Memorial Hall''',''' Olivier created a permanent site-specific installation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uknow.uky.edu/campus-news/memorial-hall-visitors-witness-new-perspective-kentucky-history|title=Memorial Hall Visitors 'Witness' New Perspective on Kentucky History|date=2018-08-24|website=UKNow|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> She reproduced the African American and Native American \ufb01gures from a controversial [[New Deal]]-era fresco inserting these images onto the domed ceiling of the vestibule, which she had gold-leafed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wuky.org/post/memorial-hall-artist-karyn-olivier-isnt-after-resolution-she-wants-more-questions|title=Memorial Hall Artist Karyn Olivier Isn&#039;t After Resolution. She Wants More Questions.|last=James|first=Josh|website=www.wuky.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> Four portraits of important (but under recognized) individuals in Kentucky's history are presented in the circular medallions below the ceiling.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kykernel.com/news/once-anonymous-now-revered-memorial-hall-art-adds-context-to/article_74cb8b22-a17c-11e8-9de3-1794587f6b46.html|title=Once anonymous, now revered: Memorial Hall art adds context to debate of race in art|last=Childress|first=Rick|website=The Kentucky Kernel|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> Around the base of the dome is a [[Frederick Douglass]] quote: \u201cThere is not a man beneath the canopy of heaven, that does not know that slavery is wrong for him.\u201d<ref name=\":6\" /> The Herald-Leader Editorial Board said \u201cWhat a beautiful \u2014 literally, beautiful \u2014 response to concerns that a New Deal-era mural at the University of Kentucky was racially insensitive to 21st century viewers.\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kentucky.com/opinion/editorials/article217940470.html|title=A picture-perfect response at the University of Kentucky|last=|first=|date=September 2018|website=Lexington Herald Reader|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''Here and Now/Glacier, Shard, Rock (2015)''' was Part of [[Creative Time]]\u2019s exhibition ''Drifting in Daylight''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://creativetime.org/projects/drifting-in-daylight/|title=Drifting in Daylight: Art in Central Park|website=Creative Time|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Olivier created a lenticular billboard that blended contrasting topographic and anthropologic histories through three images\u2014a glacier, a pottery shard from the historic [[Seneca Village]] settlement, and an image of the contemporary landscape.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://glacierhub.org/2015/06/04/artist-reawakens-glacial-past-in-central-park/|title=Artist Reawakens Glacial Past In Central Park|last=June 2015|first=Manon Verchot4|date=2015-06-04|website=GlacierHub|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> The Wisconsin Glacier travelled through what is now New York City, 20,000 years ago. Seneca Village was a vibrant Manhattan settlement founded by free black property owners who were displaced when the city claimed the right of '[[eminent domain]]' to purchase their properties and develop [[Central Park]].<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://creativetime.org/projects/drifting-in-daylight/artists/karyn-olivier/|title=Karyn Olivier|website=Creative Time|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> As noted in Nature\u2019s Nation: American Art and Environment \u201cAs one observer explained, the work \u201celegantly reminds us of the constantly mutable nature of the park and its history,\u201d including its geological past and its modern political ecology. ''Here and Now'' reframed Olmsted's picturesque landscape from Olivier's viewpoint as an African American woman attentive to human difference and non-human agency.\u201d <ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|date=2019|title=Nature\u2019s Nation: American Art and Environment|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.24926/24716839.1709|journal=Panorama|doi=10.24926/24716839.1709|issn=2471-6839}}</ref>\n\n== Awards, grants, residencies ==\n\n=== Awards ===\n\n*The Rome Prize, The American Academy in Rome, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tyler.temple.edu/tylers-karyn-olivier-wins-rome-prize|title=Tyler's Karyn Olivier wins Rome Prize|website=Tyler School of Art|language=en|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/news/american-academy-in-rome-announces-2018-19-fellows-74981|title=American Academy in Rome Announces 2018\u201319 Fellows|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n*New York Foundation for the Arts (NYFA) Award, 2011\n*William H Johnson Prize\u2013Finalist Prize, 2009\n*The Joan Mitchell Foundation Award, 2007\n*Louis Comfort Tiffany Foundation Biennial Award, 2003\n\n=== Grants ===\n\n*Harpo Foundation Grant, 2014\n*The Pollock-Krasner Foundation Grant, 2013\n*The John Simon Guggenheim Foundation Fellowship, 2007\n*Art Matters Grant, 2007\n*Creative Capital Grant, 2005\n*Emerging Artists Fellowship, Socrates Sculpture Park, Long Island City, New York, 2004\n* Cultural Arts Council of Houston and Harris County, Individual Artist Grant, 2003\n\n=== Residencies ===\n\n*Lehigh University, Horger Artist in Residence, Bethlehem, PA, 2018\n*The Cynthia Woods Mitchell Center for the Arts, University of Houston, Houston, Texas, 2009\n*The Studio Museum in Harlem, New York, New York, 2005\u20132006\n*The Marie Walsh Sharpe Foundation Space Program, New York, New York, 2004\u20132005\n*Museum of Fine Arts Houston, Core Program, Houston, Texas, 2001\u20132003\n*Skowhegan School of Painting and Sculpture, Skowhegan, Maine, 2000\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n\n=== Solo (select) ===\n2020     {{indent|5}}''\"Everything That's Alive Moves,\"'' [[Institute of Contemporary Art, Philadelphia]], January 24\u2014May 10, 2020\n\n2019     {{indent|5}}''When I See It'', Stockton University Art Gallery'','' Galloway, NJ, September 4\u2013November 12, 2019\n{{indent|5}}''Because Time In This Place Does Not Obey An Order'', Le Murate Progetti Arte Contemporanea, Florence, Italy, February 8\u2013March 16, 2019\n\n2018     {{indent|5}}''Karyn Olivier'', Lehigh University Art Galleries and Teaching Museum, Lehigh University, Bethlehem, PA, January 24\u2013May 25, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://luag.lehigh.edu/videos/artist-karyn-olivier-complexity-being-human|title=Artist Karyn Olivier - The Complexity of Being Human {{!}} Lehigh University Art Galleries|website=luag.lehigh.edu|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n2014     {{indent|5}}''Eye Around Matter'', Marso Galer\u00eda Arte Contempor\u00e1neo, Mexico City, Mexico, April 03\u2014May 31, 2014\n\n2009     {{indent|5}}''Road Signs'', Moores Opera House, University of Houston, Houston, Texas (video premiere and live performance), November 16, 2009\n\n2007     {{indent|5}}''A Closer Look,'' [[Laumeier Sculpture Park]], St. Louis, MO, February 9\u2013May 15, 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artdaily.cc/news/18458/Karyn-Olivier-at-Laumei